post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_22518680_22518680_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 775}}, "n3337": {"so_22518680_22518680_0": {"length": 5, "quality": 0.625, "section_id": 762}}}, "22518781": {"PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>The draft is in error. The final version of the C++11 standard has <code>array&lt;T, N&gt; a</code> as you would expect.</p>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-19T21:45:32.147", "Id": "22518781", "CommentCount": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-03-19T21:45:32.147", "ParentId": "22518680", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "481267"}, "22518680": {"ViewCount": "198", "Body": "<p>In the working draft <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2010/n3225.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2010/n3225.pdf</a> 23.3.2 it says </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_22518680_22518680_0\">An array is an aggregate (8.5.1) that can be initialized with the\n  syntax <code>array a&lt;T, N&gt; = { initializer-list };</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I would have throught <code>array&lt;T, N&gt; a = { initializer-list };</code> would be correct, can someone explain this odd syntax?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "22518781", "Title": "is array a<T, N> = { initializer-list }; correct syntax?", "CreationDate": "2014-03-19T21:40:31.053", "Id": "22518680", "CommentCount": "1", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2014-03-19T21:45:32.147", "Score": "4", "OwnerUserId": "893819", "Tags": "<c++><c++11>", "AnswerCount": "1"}});